Module jtamaro
Package jtamaro.data

Interface Sequence<T>

All Superinterfaces:
Iterable<T>
public interface Sequence<T> extends Iterable<T>
A Sequence is an ordered list of elements of type T, it corresponds directly to what you called "List-of-T" in PF1.

To work with a Sequence, you can use the methods in the Sequences class.

    • reversed

      Sequence<T> reversed()
      Returns a sequence that is the reverse of this one.

      Invoking this method twice should return a Sequence that is equal to this sequence: s.equals(s.reversed().reversed()).

    • intersperse

      Sequence<T> intersperse(T element)
      Inserts an element between all elements of this sequence.

      intersperse("-", of("1", "2", "3")) === of("1", "-", "2", "-", "3")

      Parameters:
      element - The element to insert
      Returns:
      A sequence with the elements of the original sequence internally separated by element

    • zipWith

      <U> Sequence<Pair<T,U>> zipWith(Sequence<U> that)
      Returns a Sequence formed by combining corresponding elements in pairs from this sequence and another given sequence.

      If one of the two sequences is longer than the other, its remaining elements are ignored. The length of the returned sequence is the minimum of the lengths of the two sequences.

      Type Parameters:
      U - The type of the elements of the other sequence
      Parameters:
      that - The other sequence of this operation. Its element will appear in the Pair.second() of the produced sequence
